      modelResponse: "The book that fundamentally altered my worldview was 'Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind' by Yuval Noah Harari. I came across it during my final year of high school, at a time when I was grappling with big questions about human existence and the direction of society. A history teacher recommended it, and I devoured it over the course of a single week.\n\nThe book traces the arc of human history from the Cognitive Revolution roughly seventy thousand years ago to the present day. Harari argues that Homo sapiens domated the planet not because of individual intelligence or strength, but because of our unique capacity for大规模 cooperation, which is enabled by shared fictions — things like money, nations, laws, and corporations that exist only in our collective imagination.\n\nWhat struck me most forcefully was the idea that many of the structures we take for granted as objective realities are actually intersubjective constructs. The concept that human rights, political borders, and economic systems are all elaborate stories we collectively believe is simultaneously unsettling and liberating. It made me realise that because we invented these systems, we also have the power to reinvent them.\n\nThis book fundamentally changed the way I approach information and authority. I became much more critical of grand narratives and more aware of the stories that shape my own beliefs. It sparked an enduring interest in anthropology and behavioural science, which eventually influenced my choice of university studies. More than any other book I have read, 'Sapiens' gave me a framework for understanding the world that continues to inform my thinking daily.",
