      modelResponse: "One of the most meaningful experiences of helping someone occurred during my second year at university when I tutored a first-year student who was struggling with organic chemistry. Her name was Priya, and she was on the verge of dropping out of her engineering program because she simply could not grasp the core concepts.\n\nPriya had fallen behind due to a combination of factors — she had been ill for several weeks and had missed critical lectures, and the subsequent material built on foundations she had never properly established. By the time I met her through the university\'s peer mentoring scheme, she was visibly demoralised and convinced that she lacked the aptitude for the subject. Her self-confidence had been severely eroded.\n\nI took a very different approach from the formal instruction she had received. Instead of drilling through textbook problems, I used analogies and visual models to explain concepts like molecular geometry and reaction mechanisms. I related abstract chemical principles to everyday phenomena — for instance, explaining oxidation-reduction reactions using the example of rust forming on a bicycle chain. I also helped her develop effective study techniques, such as active recall and spaced repetition.\n\nThe outcome was immensely gratifying. Over the course of three months, her grades improved from failing to a solid B-plus. More importantly, I witnessed a complete transformation in her attitude. She regained her confidence and rediscovered her passion for engineering. Seeing her succeed a difficult final exam with genuine enthusiasm rather than relief was deeply rewarding. It reinforced my belief that effective teaching is about unlocking potential rather than simply transmitting information.",
