      modelResponse: "The piece of technology I value most is my noise-cancelling headphones, specifically a pair of over-ear wireless headphones I purchased approximately two years ago. While it may seem a modest choice compared to smartphones or laptops, this device has had a disproportionately positive impact on my daily life.\n\nI use them in a variety of contexts. Primarily, they are essential for focused study sessions. As someone who lives in a bustling urban environment with constant ambient noise — traffic, construction, neighbours — the ability to create an instant quiet zone is invaluable. I also use them during travel; long flights become significantly more tolerable when I can immerse myself in a podcast or classical music without the drone of aircraft engines.\n\nThe technology behind them is quite sophisticated. They use active noise cancellation, which involves built-in microphones that detect ambient sound and generate inverse sound waves to neutralise it. The result is an eerie, profound silence that allows for deep concentration. The sound quality itself is excellent, with a balanced frequency response that suits a wide range of musical genres.\n\nWhat makes this device so important to me is the psychological benefit it provides. In an era of constant notifications and information overload, having the agency to control my auditory environment is empowering. It allows me to carve out pockets of uninterrupted focus in an otherwise fragmented day. This has directly improved my productivity and, perhaps more importantly, my mental well-being. It is a reminder that sometimes the most impactful technologies are those that help us disconnect rather than connect.",
