      modelResponse: "A cultural event that left a lasting impression on me was the Lunar New Year Festival held in Melbourne\'s Chinatown district this past January. I attended with a group of friends, and it turned out to be a spectacular celebration of Vietnamese and Chinese heritage that far exceeded my expectations.\n\nThe entire precinct was transformed into a vibrant tapestry of colour and sound. Red lanterns lined the streets, symbolising good fortune and prosperity, and the air was thick with the aroma of sizzling street food — everything from dumplings to banh mi to grilled satay skewers. The centrepiece was a grand stage erected at the intersection of Russell and Little Bourke Streets, where a continuous programme of performances unfolded throughout the evening.\n\nThe highlight was undoubtedly the dragon dance, a mesmerising spectacle involving a team of acrobatic performers manipulating a magnificent dragon puppet made of silk and bamboo. The dragon snaked through the crowded streets to the rhythmic beating of drums and clashing cymbals, and the energy of the crowd was electric. I also enjoyed the traditional music performances, particularly a solo on the đàn bầu, a Vietnamese monochord instrument that produces hauntingly beautiful tones.\n\nWhat I found most enriching was the sense of community and cultural pride that permeated the event. It was wonderful to see people of all backgrounds coming together to celebrate and learn about traditions that may not have been their own. The festival was a powerful reminder of the richness that cultural diversity brings to a society. I left feeling not only entertained but also genuinely moved by the beauty and depth of traditions that have been preserved for centuries.",
